              <!-- <span>Bren Hill, B.s mechanical engineering</span> -->
            </div>
            <p>When Wendy talked with me about the Cocoon retreat, I was intrigued and said yes right away. Knowing her character, integrity, and passion for helping others allowed me to enter into the experience without a need to know exactly what was going to happen. I was aware that Wendy had experienced tremendous healing through the type of work she’s involved in—all the more reason to embrace the opportunity. My decision to show up, to trust the process, and to invest myself fully in it is truly three of the best decisions I’ve ever made.I was in need of healing myself. For the last 17 years, I’ve been dealing with a stress-driven thyroid conversion disorder that was difficult to diagnose, and even more difficult to treat. The main symptom that presented with this condition was a complete loss of vocal function. I was initially diagnosed with Spasmodic Dysphonia—a vocal disorder with no known cause and no known cure, and when I began researching the condition I discovered that like myself, most people who are affected by it have histories of severe stress. Through prayer, I was able to identify the true cause of the problem, and was able to recover thanks to finding a thyroid protocol that works for me. Still, I’ve had to be extremely careful not to overtax my body, and have had side effects to deal with—the most troublesome of which was an increased heart rate.When the retreat began, I was at a loss as to how the exercises we engaged in could have any real effect on me physically, mentally, or spiritually; however, I decided to disconnect from my rational mind and simply experience what was being offered. The more I let go and trusted the safe environment that was provided and the people around me, the more I was able to access things that felt like they had been buried deep within me for years. Alternately, I wept, laughed, screamed, and sobbed, yet what I was experiencing could not be tied to any three situation or circumstance. I didn’t need to know where it was coming from or why I felt that way, I just needed to release it—or more accurately, to let it be. Just when I felt there couldn’t possibly be anything else to deal with, waves of emotion would rise to the surface yet again. I was amazed that I could be that vulnerable in the presence of people I had never met before and that they in kind could share the deepest parts of themselves with me. The people I shared this experience with are like brothers and sisters to me, and I have a bond with them that defies explanation.Shortly after the retreat I saw my doctor for my six-month thyroid check and my heart rate was normal at that visit for the first time in over 5 years. Although I’ve always considered myself to be emotionally open, I am finding that I am connecting with people more easily—even total strangers. I have less mental and physical stress, and am more able to step back and take a deep breath in emotionally charged situations. The time I spend meditating is richer and when I pray, I am physically affected by my connection with God—it’s as if I’m plugged into the source of all life and love is pulsing throughout my body. I have been doing serious self-improvement/spiritual work for many years and nothing I have dthree has been as strong as this work. I believe that my life has been forever changed by this experience and I am so grateful that I was able to be a part of it.</p>
